<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>Written evidence from the Transport Research Laboratory (TRL) (SLC 023)</title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:14pt">Written evidence from the Transport Research Laboratory (TRL) (SLC 023)</span></p><p style="line-height:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="line-height:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">Introduction</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; line-height:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 15pt; padding-left:3pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">The Transport Research Laboratory (</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">TRL</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">)</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> is one of the largest and most comprehensive independent transport ‘centres of excellence’ in the world. Established over 80 years ago, we provide a broad range of technical consultancy, research and development, technology and product testing services. T</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">RL has helped to shape the modern transport environment by developing standards, guides and policy advice in all aspects of surface transportation. Our work is supported by world class testing and certification facilities which include impact rigs, a struc</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">tures hall, accelerated testing facilities, simulators, dynamic asset survey and monitoring services.</span></li><li style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; line-height:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 15pt; padding-left:3pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">As a multi-disciplinary organisation, TRL works across a wide spectrum of fields in the transport sector, including highway, urban and rural road design, </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">construction and maintenance, railways, asset management, road and rail safety, transport planning, sustainable transport, intelligent transport systems, socio-economic assessments, climate change mitigation and adaptation, and environmental assessment. Th</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">rough our work, TRL sets standards for highway and vehicle design, develops, monitors and evaluates transport policies, innovates and improves transport systems and their impact on the environment, and encourages good engineering practice. Our technical ev</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">idence and reports are frequently cited and used in policy and decision making in both the public and private sectors. </span></li><li style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; line-height:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 15pt; padding-left:3pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><a name="_Ref367192487"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">TRL ha</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> studied issues surrounding level crossings on both public roads and private roads in projects for RSSB, DfT and ORR. </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">There are o</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">ver 6,500 level crossings in Great Britain</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> and different types of crossings are protected in different ways. On public roads, level crossings </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">can be classified as barrier crossings, gated crossings </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">and open crossings:</span></a></li><ol type="a" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; line-height:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 50.64pt; padding-left:3.36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">Barrier crossings have barriers that e</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">ither cover the whole carriageway or half the carriageway, along with light signals and an audible alarm.  </span></li><li style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; line-height:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 50.87pt; padding-left:3.13pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">Gated crossings have gates on both sides of the railway and are opened and closed by railway staff. These types of crossings do not usually have lig</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">ht signals or an audible alarm.</span></li><li style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; line-height:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 49.85pt; padding-left:4.15pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">Open crossings do not have any barriers or gates. Some open crossings are protected by light signals and an audible alarm whilst others are not.</span></li></ol><li style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; line-height:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 15pt; padding-left:3pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">On private roads, level crossings usually have barriers or gates that are opera</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">ted by the person using the crossing and these are known as user worked crossings. </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">They</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> sometimes have a telephone and light signals present. </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">There are over 2</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">600</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> user </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">worked level crossings in Great Britain, making them a relatively common category of cro</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">ssing. When related to usage rates, the risk at these types of crossings is relatively high when compared with other types of level crossing. </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">TRL therefore recommend that the safety of user-worked crossings is considered as well as</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">the types of crossings o</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">utlined in paragraph </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">3</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">.</span></li><li style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; line-height:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 15pt; padding-left:3pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">TRL is pleased to</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> provide the following evidence</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">on the safety of level crossings to the Transport Committee.</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> TRL would be willing to provide further details and </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">to </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">present evidence </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">to the C</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">ommittee if required.</span></li></ol><p style="line-height:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">Are current safety measures at level crossing adequate? How should they be improved?</span></p><p style="line-height:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; text-decoration:underline">Level crossings on public roads</span></p><ol start="6" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; line-height:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 15pt; padding-left:3pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">TRL </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">has </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">conducted research into the </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">signs, signals and road markings at level crossings on public roads to determine whether the current regime is fit for purpose and to identify and evaluate potential improvements. </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">TRL </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">has </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">also conducted separate research into provisions that may assist peo</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">ple with disabilities when using level crossings. This group of pedestrians may be affected by a loss of sight, hearing, cognition and/or mobility. When using a level crossing with a disability, there is potential for safety to be compromised if the existi</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">ng infrastructure and signals are not accessible to all types of users. The combined outcomes of these research studies</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">suggest</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> that level crossings c</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">ould</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> be improved in the following ways:</span></li><li style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; line-height:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 15pt; padding-left:3pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><a name="_Ref367450729"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">Late braking, becoming stranded between the barriers and failing t</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">o observe the level crossing are associated with higher levels of risk for road vehicles. Improving the design and salience of information could increase road users’ awareness of level crossings.</span></a></li><ol type="a" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; line-height:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 50.64pt; padding-left:3.36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">Road user comprehension of the current level crossing advanc</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">e warning signs is low. One universal level crossing advance warning sign replac</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">ing</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> the signs that are currently used</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> could improve this situation</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">.</span></li><li style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; line-height:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 50.87pt; padding-left:3.13pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><a name="_Ref367196417"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">Vibrotactile warnings, such as rumble strips, which start before the driver reaches the level crossing advan</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">ce warning sign could be installed</span></a><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> to capture and direct driver attention, and draw attention to the advance warning sign.</span></li><li style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; line-height:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 49.85pt; padding-left:4.15pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">Skirts </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">c</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">ould be installed under all barriers that do not currently have any</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> to increase visual impact</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> In addition, installing barrie</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">rs at level crossing where there are not any could increase rates of detection.</span></li></ol><li style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; line-height:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 15pt; padding-left:3pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">Yellow box markings provided across the surface of all level crossings </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">is likely </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">to encourage </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">more </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">drivers to check that their exit is clear before moving onto the </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">crossing.</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> </span></li><li style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; line-height:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 15pt; padding-left:3pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">A simpler, novel sign instructing drivers of large or slow vehicles to stop and phone for permission before crossing </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">is recommended to </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">replace the current s</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">ign. The design of the current sign</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> does not comply with good practice as the written message is ver</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">y long and measurements are presented in imperial units only.</span></li><li style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; line-height:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><a name="_Ref367196430"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">The area close to the crossing where parking is not permitted should be clearly marked.</span></a></li><li style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; line-height:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">An audible alarm is provided at some types of level crossing</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> and in some instances the audible alarm chang</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">es in pitch after the first train has passed if the crossing will remain closed for another train</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">Our research shows that t</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">he change in pitch of an abstract sound does not convey the correct message clearly and it is recommended that a</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> well understood aud</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">ible warning</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">be </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">developed</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> Dynamic volume adjustment to ensure continuous audibility above the prevalent level of background noise is </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">also </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">desirable. As well as assisting all users, this is of specific benefit to pedestrians who are hard of hearing and pedestrians with sight loss. Pedestrians with sight loss rely on the audible warnings as the primary indicator of an approaching train (especi</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">ally at open and half barrier crossings). </span></li><li style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; line-height:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">Slips, trips and falls are associated with the highest level of risk for pedestrians. These instances could be mitigated by better maintenance of the crossing surface </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">and</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">clearer marking of the rails or other perm</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">anent undulations in the road. Level</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">, consistent and rubberised crossing surfaces for pedestrians that are distinctly different from the surfaces used for </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">the</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> footways</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> that approach the crossing are also recommended</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">This would assist</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> pedestrians with sigh</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">t loss </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">to </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">detect </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">the crossing surface and also benefit</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> pedestrians with </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">other </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">disabilities </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">by further defining the crossing and ensuring it is uniform and</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> not</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> physical</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">ly </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">demanding to cross.</span></li><li style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; line-height:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">L</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">evel and consistent surface</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> for </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">the</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> footways</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> that approach the c</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">rossing (where provided) </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">that </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">are</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> distinctly different from the crossing surface itself</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> are expected to help pedestrians with sight loss to detect level crossings reliably. Benefits also exist for all pedestrians with disabilities as the crossing itself be</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">comes a clearer feature on the highway. </span></li><li style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; line-height:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">The pedestrian footway should be clearly delineated from the carriageway</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> and </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">this </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">may be more important at locations where it is safer </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">for pedestrians</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> to use a particular side of the carri</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">ag</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">eway</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">. Tactile longitudina</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">l white guidelines are recommended for the edges of the footway over the level crossing to assist pedestrians with sight loss (and pedestrians in general) to navigate a safe path over the crossing that does not bring them into conflict with vehicles or the</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> track. </span></li><li style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; line-height:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">Being struck by level crossing equipment was also associated with a high level of risk for pedestrians. The decision point / stop point for road users should be clearly delineated so that it is separate from the level crossing surface and the area</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> below the barriers.</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> This could include a marked s</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">urface to warn pedestrians </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">where it is not safe to stand due to the risk of being struck by a lowering barrier. This would benefit deaf pedestrians who cannot hear the audible warning, as well as other grou</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">ps who may be unaware of the hazard presented when the barriers descend.</span></li><li style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; line-height:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">Wig-wag </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">light signals</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">c</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">ould be upgraded from incandescent bulbs to LEDs to improve signal visibility for all users. </span></li><li style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; line-height:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">Colour contrast for wig-wag</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> light signal</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> posts</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> is recommended</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">. Thi</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">s benefits pedestrians with sight loss and other groups with identifying and navigating crossings without colliding into wig-wag posts on the footways.</span></li><li style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; line-height:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">There </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">c</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">ould be wider use of the flashing red man pedestrian signal to help all pedestrians identify the </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">crossing and assist specific disability groups with knowing when it is not safe to cross. This signal is particularly useful when there is poor line of sight to a crossing from an approaching footway (the wig-wag signal and barriers—if fitted— may not be v</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">isible to road users approaching the crossing from an angle).</span></li><li style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; line-height:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">C</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">orduroy </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">tactile paving</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> surfaces before transverse </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">painted </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">footway lines on </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">the</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">footway </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">approaches to all level crossings</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> are desirable to help people with sight loss who need to identify that t</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">here is a level crossing ahead. </span></li><li style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; line-height:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">Improved consistency for the transverse footway stop lines, by ensuring that they are used at all crossings with a footway and are applied in a consistent form (i.e. a solid painted white line) is desirable. These lines red</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">uce confusion for all pedestrians and assist pedestrians who have residual vision, hearing loss and/or learning disabilities with identifying a safe place to stop and wait at the crossing if it is closed. </span></li><li style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; line-height:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">N</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">on-reflective materials </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">are recommended for the c</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">rossing surface to prevent reflected glare from the crossing which can disorient and temporarily ‘blind’ pedestrians with sight loss, as well as other users, including drivers.</span></li><li style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; line-height:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">C</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">onsistent, colour-contrasting fencing </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">around</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> barrier lifting mechanism</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> and le</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">vel crossing area</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> is recommended</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">. This benefits pedestrians with sight loss and other groups with identifying and navigating the crossing without colliding with hazardous obstructions.</span></li><li style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; line-height:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">The</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">r</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">ecommendations in paragraphs 7 to</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> 22</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> represent the combined findi</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">ngs of our research into improvements to the signs, signals and other features at level crossings. It is desirable fo</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">r any programme of change to be</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> applied consistently so that users experience the same features at each type of level crossing</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">, as well as </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">at crossings of the same type</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">The variety of signs and signals that road users are required to see, read, interpret and respond to </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">would thereby </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">be minimised. </span></li><li style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; line-height:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">While many of the recommended features are suggested as solutions to assist people with disabil</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">ities, it is generally recognised that an accessible design is also the highest design standard. </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">It is anticipated that t</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">he vast majority of improvements that would make crossings more accessible to users with disabilities would also improve the visibility</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> and usability of level crossings for a wide range of other road users. </span></li></ol><p style="line-height:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; text-decoration:underline">Level crossings on private road</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; text-decoration:underline">s (user worked crossings)</span></p><ol start="25" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; line-height:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">Information and warnings, and the layout of these measures, often varies between the approaches to one crossing and between di</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">fferent crossings. It is recommended that the signs and signals at user worked crossings, and their positions, are used more consistently. </span></li><li style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; line-height:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">The information provided </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">on </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">instruction signs for drivers could be improved</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> by addressing the messages and designs</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">There is a lot of text to read on these signs and the terminology </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">is found confusing by some users according to our research</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">. In addition, the signs used at crossing</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> with and without telephone</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">s are of a similar design</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> to each other</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> despite </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">the requirement</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> for </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">different procedures</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">to be carried out</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">. </span></li><li style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; line-height:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">Some user worked crossings have a very large number of level crossing related signs installed</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> which results in sign clutter and </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">this </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">could lead to information overload. Minimising the number of signs, signals </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">and road markings that road users are required to see, read, interpret and respond to, and only providing safety-critical information, could lead to improved safety.</span></li><li style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; line-height:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">Improving maintenance of information and warnings as well as the surrounding environment c</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">ould improve safety at user worked crossings. This may also have a positive impact on attitudes of crossing users who may perceive that safety at user worked crossings is important to Network Rail.</span></li><li style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; line-height:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">Pedestrians must cross the railway tracks on foot once whe</