font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">edestrians look down on the approach to</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> level crossings</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> so traffic signs might not always be the best way to present information</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">. Pr</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">esenting warnings</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">, information and alerts</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> on the ground might increase awareness</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">.</span></li></ol><p style="line-height:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt; page-break-after:avoid; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; text-decoration:underline">The effect of traffic delays on safety at level crossings</span></p><ol start="32" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; line-height:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">A separate stream of research at TRL considered the effect that traffic delays can have on the safety of all level crossing users, as well as those road user</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">s in the vicinity of the crossing. TRL conducted a review and consultation of the issues related to traffic delays at level crossings on behalf of the </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">DfT</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">. The study did not investigate whether current safety measures at level crossings were adequate; inst</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">ead it investigated which measures at active public road level crossings created safe and unsafe situations with regard to vehicle traffic, with a view to making recommendations for future research and mitigation. The focus was on active level crossings</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">; </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">i</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">.e. those crossings that warn users of an approaching train rather than passive crossings that are controlled by signs only (open) or by users (on private land). </span></li><li style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; line-height:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><a name="_Ref367282115"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">Serious traffic delay at a level crossing (which is without a universally agreed definition) </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">may prompt risky road user behaviour in and around the crossing. Blocking back is one example</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">; </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">i.e. vehicles enter the crossing area when their exit is blocked due to traffic ahead of them thus creating an obstacle on the crossing</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">O</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">ther examples include r</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">ed light-running, yellow box violations at junctions near the crossing, driving on footways, driving on the wrong side of the road and zigzagging around the barriers at half barrier crossings. All of these examples could be considered hazardous to the safe</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">ty of road and/or rail users. Other related concerns include the impact of vehicle emissions on the local community (both noise and tailpipe emissions), the impact on businesses of queuing traffic outside their premises and the potential for community seve</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">rance when a crossing divides an area and is not considered to be readily accessible.</span></a><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> </span></li><li style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; line-height:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">Our study found that m</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">anually controlled barrier </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">(MCB) </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">crossings (with or without CCTV) </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">were more commonly associated with road</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> traffic delays, </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">primarily because</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> they re</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">quire the barrier to be closed for some time before the arrival of the train</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> (longer than a crossing with automatic protection)</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">, and they tend to be located where there is a higher level of road traffic.</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> </span></li><li style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; line-height:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">MCB crossing protection is the highest level of pro</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">tection available for a level crossing. It is sometimes fitted to existing crossings as a solution to the safety hazard of vehicles blocking back at locations where existing traffic problems create risks at open or half barrier automatic crossings. Whilst </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">MCB crossings increase the protection (and therefore decrease the risk of using a lower level of crossing protection), they have other consequences that could be construed as providing an ‘unsafe’ environment at the crossing. These effects can manifest as </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">traffic delays, which can lead to further issues.</span></li><li style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; line-height:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">Blocking back remains one of these issues: although </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">an approaching train will not receive a signal to proceed </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">if there is a vehicle on </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">a manually controlled </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">crossing, vehicles may still wait on the crossing when the barriers are open, thus delaying barrier closure. If this becomes a frequent occurrence, the crossing will often be </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">closed further in advance of a train to reduce delays to the railway. This may ex</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">acerbate road traffic delay by increasing the total time that the crossing is closed. The other concerns for safety are those </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">highlighted in paragraph</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">33</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> </span></li><li style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; line-height:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">Our study proceeded to explore, in consultation with rail and highway stakeholders, what options wer</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">e available to mitigate the problem of traffic delays at levels crossings and the inherent safety concerns that accompanied such delays. </span></li><li style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; line-height:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">It was recognised that t</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">he most effective means of redu</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">cing delay (and lowering risk) i</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">s to close the level crossing. </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">However this has many attendant obstacles to implementation, not least of which is the financial aspect, and bridging/underpass is almost impossible at level crossings with dense housing in close proximity.</span></li><li style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; line-height:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><a name="_Ref367373072"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">Alternative recommendations were considered in th</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">e study.</span></a><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> </span></li><ol type="a" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; line-height:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 50.64pt; padding-left:3.36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">The first of these recommendations was to develop a universal </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">defin</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">ition of ‘serious traffic delay’</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> that takes into account impacts on the community</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> and identifies the extent to which a level crossing contributes to delay</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">.  I</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">n some locations, </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">red</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">ucing delay at level crossing</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">if</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> there is already serious congestion in the surrounding network may be a fruitless exercise.</span></li><li style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; line-height:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 50.87pt; padding-left:3.13pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">The second of these recommendations was to ensure </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">more frequent and improved interaction between road and rail authorities, and </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">th</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">e</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> further inclusion of town planners</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> when discussing the integration of level crossings</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">The report identified several </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">Road Rail Partnership Group</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> (RRPG</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">) </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">for road and rail</span><span style="font-family:Verdan