ily:Verdana; font-size:10pt">ost of keeping a level crossing open to</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">assist in the formation of a business case to determine whether</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">an alternative such as a bridge or underpass is likely to be cost</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">effective.</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">AXIAT could be used in conjunction with RRPGs to help discussions about fut</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">ure options for particular level crossings (by providing a clearer indication of whether or not it is a r</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">ealistic proposition to close a</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> crossing, or whether efforts are better focused on finding other solutions to traffic delays and safety concerns). </span></li><li style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; line-height:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 50.87pt; padding-left:3.13pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">The</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> fourth recommendation was to investigate </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">alternatives to upgrading protection </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">to manually controlled barriers </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">at </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">automatic half barrier</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> crossings affected by blocking back</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">. Automatic crossings create substantially shorter delays to road traffic so it is beneficial to preserve them if alternative measures can be taken to mitigate the risks presented by road users that choose to violate the crossing protection. </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">For </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">example</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">, t</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">he use of obstacle detection </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">(</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">in conjunction with Automatic Full Barriers</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">)</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> might achieve a small </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">reduction in delay compared to manual crossing</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">without</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> compromising safety.</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> Alternat</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">ively, measures could be taken o</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">n together with the local highway authorit</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">y to reduce the reasons for blocking block (e.g. by </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">eliminating a right-turn after a crossing, or installing a filter lane for this purpose). </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">  </span></li></ol></ol><p style="line-height:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="line-height:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">In addition to bridges and underpasses what other cost-effective measures can be introduced to replace or impr</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">ove safety at level crossings?</span></p><ol start="40" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; line-height:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">The measures </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">discussed</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> in paragraphs </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">7</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">to </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">39</span><a name="_GoBack"></a><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> could be introduced to improve safety at level crossings.</span></li></ol><p style="line-height:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="line-height:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">How should expenditure on improving safety at level crossings be prioritised in relation to other demands on the rail bud</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">get?</span></p><ol start="41" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; line-height:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">No comments.</span></li></ol><p style="line-height:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="line-height:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; fon